07716nam a22011055i 9783110661811DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106618117 a10.1515/97831106618112doi  a(DE-B1597)531871  a(OCoLC)1138503812  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPT7321+ 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a340-34900aNarrating Law and Laws of Narration in Medieval Scandinavia /ced. by Roland Scheel. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (X, 293 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aErgänzungsbände zum Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde ,x1866-7678 ;v11700tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tContents -- tList of Contributors -- tNarrating Law and Laws of Narration: Introduction -- tPart A. Narrating Law: Legal Texts – Narrative Texts – Contexts -- tChieftains and the Legal Culture in Iceland c. 1100–1260 -- tMaking King Hákon Great Again: Law, God, Morality and Power in Björgvin, 1223 -- tLaw Personified. The Ignored Climactic Speeches of Brennu-Njáls saga -- tPart B. Laws of Narration: Narratological Approaches -- tCourt Poetry: Assemblies and Skaldic Verse -- tWhat is ‘Good Law’? Law as Communal Performance in the Íslendingasögur -- tRevenge or Settlement? Law and Feud in Early Sagas of Icelanders -- tPart C. Narrating Law: Discourses on Social Norms -- tBerserks Behaving Badly: Manipulating Normative Expectations in Eyrbyggja saga -- tSocial and Diegetic Hierarchies in Cases of Thievery. A Study of Mǫðruvallabók -- tPart D. Narrating Law: Mythological Traditions -- tFeudal Law and Archaic Order: The Discussion of Different Social Systems in the Queens’ Dispute in the Nibelungenlied -- tHistory or Idea? The Legendary Laws of Old Norsemen -- tVǫlundr – a Gateway into the Legal World of the Vikings -- tTýr, Fenrir and the Brísingamen. Tales of Law, Crime and Violence in Eddic Mythology and their Indo-European Subcontexts -- tName Index -- tPlace Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisputes lie at the heart of the sagas. Consequently, literary texts have been treated as sources of legal practice – narrations of law – while the sagas themselves and the handling of legal matters by the figures adhere to ‘laws of narration’. The volume addresses this intricate relationship between literature and social practice from the perspective of historians as well as philologists. The contributions focus not only on disputes and their solution in saga literature, but also on the representation of law and its history in sagas and Latin historiography from Scandinavia as well as the representation of laws and norms in mythological texts. They demonstrate that narrations of law provide an indispensable insight into legal culture and its connection to a wider framework of social norms, adjusting the impression given by the laws. The philological approaches underline that the narrative texts also have an agenda of their own when it comes to their representation of law, providing a mirror of conduct, criticising inequity, reinforcing the political and juridical position of kings or negotiating norms in mythological texts. Altogether, the volume underlines the unifying force exerted by a common fiction of law beyond its letter.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aLaw in literature. 0aLawzScandinaviaxHistory. 0aSagasxHistory and criticism. 4aLiteratur und Recht. 4aSage. 4aSkandinavien / Geschichtsschreibung. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aLiterature and law.  aScandinavian historiography.  asaga literature.1 aBurrows, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Daniela, econ